{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1508cf36-5957-43eb-83b2-fc6ba0ad129f","content":"Here's my assessment — **not quite ready to publish**. The template is well-structured but has a few gaps:\n\n**What's good:**\n- `identity`, `name`, `shortName`, `author`, `sourceName`, `classifications`, `tags` — all present and valid.\n- `symbols` section with a framework choice is clean.\n\n**Issues to address before publishing:**\n\n1. **Missing `$schema`** — Add `\"$schema\": \"http://json.schemastore.org/template\"` for editor validation and to signal spec compliance.\n\n2. **Missing `description`** — NuGet gallery and `dotnet new` search both use this. Without it, users won't know what the template does.\n\n3. **Missing `groupIdentity`** — Recommended when you plan to ship multiple versions/variants (e.g., `MyCompany.WebApi`). Helps NuGet group related templates.\n\n4. **No packaging project** — There's no `.csproj` or `.nuspec` to produce a NuGet package. You'll need a `templatepack.csproj` with `<PackageType>Template</PackageType>` to run `dotnet pack`.\n\n5. **`defaultValue: \"net9.0\"` but no `replaces`** — The `Framework` symbol won't substitute into your project file unless you add `\"replaces\": \"net9.0\"` (or wire it via `sourceName`).\n\nWant me to fix these issues?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9d5f3982-81a8-4110-bec3-572abc2a87a3","outputTokens":340},"id":"f6e12ba4-9f84-4469-b3ad-e432a5a08f08","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:37:11.733Z","parentId":"741d6980-6739-45b3-b477-45a8988bb4d8"}
